---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is the difference between Declarative and Scripted Pipeline?",
    answer: "Declarative Pipeline is the modern recommended syntax — it uses a structured pipeline {} block with predefined sections (agent, stages, post) that enforce best practices and provide better error messages. Scripted Pipeline is Groovy-based (node {} block), giving you full programmatic control but requiring more Groovy knowledge. Use Declarative unless you need dynamic logic that Declarative cannot express."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I validate Jenkinsfile syntax without running the pipeline?",
    answer: "Use the Jenkins CLI: curl --user user:token -X POST -F 'jenkinsfile=<Jenkinsfile' https://jenkins.example.com/pipeline-model-converter/validate. Alternatively, use the Jenkins Replay feature to test modified scripts, or integrate the Jenkins Linter VS Code extension that validates syntax on save. The declarative linter catches syntax errors before any agents are allocated."
  },
  {
    question: "What are Jenkins Shared Libraries and when should I use them?",
    answer: "Shared Libraries let you define reusable Groovy functions and pipeline steps in a separate Git repository, then import them across all your Jenkinsfiles with @Library('my-lib'). Use them when multiple pipelines share the same build/deploy/notify logic — it eliminates copy-paste drift. Store the library at vars/ (global callable steps) and src/ (Groovy classes). Configure the library in Jenkins → Manage Jenkins → Configure System → Global Pipeline Libraries."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I run pipeline stages in parallel?",
    answer: "Use the parallel directive inside a stage: parallel { stage('Unit Tests') { steps { sh 'npm test' } } stage('Lint') { steps { sh 'npm run lint' } } }. Parallel stages run simultaneously on the same or different agents. Add failFast: true as a sibling to parallel to abort all branches immediately when one fails. Jenkins 2.x supports parallel stages natively in Declarative Pipeline."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I handle post-build actions like notifications and cleanup?",
    answer: "Use the post {} block at the pipeline or stage level. It supports always (always runs), success, failure, unstable, changed (status changed from previous run), and cleanup (runs after all other post conditions). Example: post { failure { slackSend(message: 'Build failed!') } always { cleanWs() } }. The always block is ideal for archiving artifacts and workspace cleanup regardless of outcome."
  },
  {
    question: "Jenkins vs GitHub Actions vs CircleCI — which should I pick?",
    answer: "Jenkins gives you maximum flexibility and is ideal for complex enterprise pipelines with on-prem requirements, but requires maintenance of the Jenkins server itself. GitHub Actions is the easiest path for GitHub-hosted repos — zero infrastructure, marketplace of 10,000+ actions, free for public repos. CircleCI excels at test parallelism and build speed with its orbs ecosystem. For new greenfield projects on GitHub, GitHub Actions is the default choice. Jenkins remains dominant in enterprises with existing infrastructure."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Jenkins Pipeline: Jenkinsfile Syntax, Stages & Shared Libraries Guide"
  description="Complete Jenkins Pipeline reference: Declarative vs Scripted syntax, stages and steps, parallel execution, shared libraries, and post-build actions. Includes comparison with GitHub Actions and CircleCI."
  tool="Jenkins Pipeline, Jenkinsfile, declarative pipeline, shared libraries, CI/CD, Jenkins stages"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"WebPage","name":"Jenkins Pipeline: Jenkinsfile Syntax, Stages & Shared Libraries Guide","url":"https://devplaybook.cc/tools/jenkins-pipeline-syntax-checker","description":"Complete Jenkins Pipeline reference covering Declarative vs Scripted syntax, stages, parallel execution, shared libraries, and CI/CD comparisons."})} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Jenkins Pipeline: Jenkinsfile Syntax, Stages & Shared Libraries</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Jenkins Pipeline is the backbone of CI/CD in thousands of enterprises. Whether you are writing your first Jenkinsfile or migrating from Scripted to Declarative syntax, this guide covers everything from basic stage structure to advanced shared library patterns — with working code examples you can copy today.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Declarative &amp; Scripted Pipeline syntax</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Parallel stages &amp; failFast</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Shared Libraries setup</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Post-build actions &amp; notifications</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Jenkins vs GitHub Actions vs CircleCI</span>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />

  <div class="mt-8 space-y-8">

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Declarative Pipeline Structure</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Declarative Pipeline is the recommended approach for most teams. The <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">pipeline</code> block enforces a clear structure: <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">agent</code>, <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">environment</code>, <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">stages</code>, and <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">post</code>. Jenkins validates the syntax before any agent is allocated, giving you faster feedback on configuration errors.</p>
      <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm font-mono text-gray-300"><code>// Jenkinsfile (Declarative Pipeline)
pipeline &#123;
  agent any

  environment &#123;
    NODE_VERSION = '20'
    DEPLOY_ENV   = 'staging'
  &#125;

  stages &#123;
    stage('Install') &#123;
      steps &#123;
        sh 'npm ci'
      &#125;
    &#125;
    stage('Test') &#123;
      steps &#123;
        sh 'npm test -- --ci --coverage'
      &#125;
      post &#123;
        always &#123;
          junit 'coverage/junit.xml'
        &#125;
      &#125;
    &#125;
    stage('Build') &#123;
      steps &#123;
        sh 'npm run build'
        archiveArtifacts artifacts: 'dist/**', fingerprint: true
      &#125;
    &#125;
    stage('Deploy') &#123;
      when &#123;
        branch 'main'
      &#125;
      steps &#123;
        sh './scripts/deploy.sh $&#123;DEPLOY_ENV&#125;'
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;

  post &#123;
    failure &#123;
      slackSend(color: 'danger', message: "Build failed: $&#123;env.JOB_NAME&#125; #$&#123;env.BUILD_NUMBER&#125;")
    &#125;
    always &#123;
      cleanWs()
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Parallel Stages</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Running stages in parallel dramatically reduces total pipeline duration. Jenkins allocates separate executors for each parallel branch. Use <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">failFast: true</code> to cancel all other branches the moment one fails — essential for fast feedback in large test suites.</p>
      <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm font-mono text-gray-300"><code>stage('Parallel Checks') &#123;
  parallel &#123;
    stage('Unit Tests') &#123;
      steps &#123; sh 'npm run test:unit' &#125;
    &#125;
    stage('Integration Tests') &#123;
      steps &#123; sh 'npm run test:integration' &#125;
    &#125;
    stage('Lint') &#123;
      steps &#123; sh 'npm run lint' &#125;
    &#125;
    stage('Security Scan') &#123;
      steps &#123; sh 'npm audit --audit-level=high' &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
  // abort all branches when any one fails
  failFast true
&#125;</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Shared Libraries</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Shared Libraries eliminate copy-paste across Jenkinsfiles. Define reusable steps in a dedicated Git repository under <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">vars/</code> and import them with <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">@Library</code>. Configure the library URL in Jenkins → Manage Jenkins → Configure System → Global Pipeline Libraries.</p>
      <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm font-mono text-gray-300"><code>// vars/deployApp.groovy  (in your shared library repo)
def call(String environment, String appName) &#123;
  echo "Deploying $&#123;appName&#125; to $&#123;environment&#125;"
  sh "kubectl set image deployment/$&#123;appName&#125; app=$&#123;appName&#125;:$&#123;env.BUILD_NUMBER&#125; -n $&#123;environment&#125;"
  sh "kubectl rollout status deployment/$&#123;appName&#125; -n $&#123;environment&#125;"
&#125;

// Jenkinsfile  (in your application repo)
@Library('my-shared-library') _

pipeline &#123;
  agent any
  stages &#123;
    stage('Deploy to Staging') &#123;
      steps &#123;
        deployApp('staging', 'my-api')
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Jenkins vs GitHub Actions vs CircleCI</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700">
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">Feature</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">Jenkins</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">GitHub Actions</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">CircleCI</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Infrastructure</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Self-hosted (required)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Cloud or self-hosted</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Cloud or self-hosted</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Config format</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Groovy DSL (Jenkinsfile)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">YAML (.github/workflows)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">YAML (.circleci/config.yml)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Free tier</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Free (self-host costs)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Free public repos; 2,000 min/mo private</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">6,000 free credits/mo</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Parallelism</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">parallel {} block</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">matrix strategy</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">parallelism key (test splitting)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Reusable logic</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Shared Libraries</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Reusable Workflows / Actions</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Orbs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Best for</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Enterprise, on-prem, complex pipelines</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">GitHub-hosted projects, open source</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Large test suites needing speed</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Key Best Practices</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-text-muted">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5">✓</span><span><strong class="text-white">Pin agent images.</strong> Use <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">agent &#123; docker &#123; image 'node:20-alpine' &#125; &#125;</code> to ensure reproducible builds across all runs.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5">✓</span><span><strong class="text-white">Use credentials binding.</strong> Reference secrets via <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">withCredentials([string(credentialsId: 'API_KEY', variable: 'KEY')])</code> — never hardcode secrets.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5">✓</span><span><strong class="text-white">Gate deploys with when conditions.</strong> Use <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">when &#123; branch 'main' &#125;</code> to prevent feature branches from deploying to production accidentally.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5">✓</span><span><strong class="text-white">Archive test reports.</strong> Use <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">junit</code> and <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">publishHTML</code> to make test results visible in the Jenkins UI without digging through logs.</span></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

  </div>

  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
